english:
  title: Farewell Message to Shin Gong, Prefectural Commander of Kyongwon
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The state received the Mandate of Heaven and took dominion over the Great East, restoring the northeastern territories of old Goryeo. Among these lands, Gongju stands most remote and desolate. Through the Yuan's decline, its villages emptied and thorns overgrew the fields for decades. Our Late Majesty founded the great enterprise, elevated four generations of ancestors to kingship, bestowed the posthumous name of Mok Wang upon the High Progenitor, and recognizing that his burial mound lies here, honored it with the title Deok Mausoleum. He elevated the prefecture to Kyongwon and gathered scattered peoples to build a great garrison. Yet the terrain runs deep and treacherous, bordered by the wild folk whose moods shift like mountain storms—now docile as subjects, now fierce as beasts. To restrain them through benevolence proves difficult; to govern them through righteousness, harder still. This duty surpasses the trials of all other provinces. When selecting officials for this post, the court always chooses with utmost care.

    In the autumn of Eul-yu, we appointed my elder cousin Park Yong, advanced in rank to Gason, as Prefectural Commander—a position of grave responsibility. Through his breadth of spirit and trustworthy bearing, he won the people's favor. Yet when winter of Jeong-hae came and his term ended, finding a successor proved vexing until Heaven provided my younger cousin Shin Gong, who had previously held ministerial rank. That he should leave the capital to govern this distant province marks a turning point of great significance.

    The Prince summoned him to the audience hall and spoke thus: "When I dwelt in the Eastern Palace, you aided in our defense with unwavering devotion. I treasured your loyalty then, and treasuring it remain. Though you have served far afield repeatedly without complaint, each post has seen your accomplishments flourish. Now, desiring to ease our eastern concerns, none but you can suffice. I entrust this charge to you—go with careful diligence." Shin Gong replied: "I possess no special talent, only a loyal heart. How could I not exhaust myself in service? Yet I fear my nature runs swift, and I may offend the people." The Prince smiled and answered: "Though swift of temperament, you have never erred. The choice rests with me alone—why heed what others say?" Unable to demur further, Shin Gong prepared to depart.

    Being myself afflicted with illness, I could not see him off, yet I sent these words:

    "Since childhood orphaned at eight, first by your father's death in battle, then by your mother's passing, you were raised by your uncle amid hardship and sorrow. Yet from youth you showed keenness and courage. When you turned to learning, you grasped the greater meanings, then abandoned scholarship for the arts of archery and the sword. In military service, you achieved repeated victories over Japanese raiders, earning renown for valor. Twice you served in the Ministry of Justice with rigid rectitude, rendering verdicts both clear and fair. Wherever you governed—in Isan, Kangnung, Uiju—you remained unblemished and unmoved by temptation. The people first feared you, then came to love you; even after your departure, they remembered you with longing. Thus you inherited the ancient virtue of leaving the people's affection behind.

    "Yet your nature runs severe and exacting. When you perceive another's fault, you cannot forbear but must speak it aloud with fierce reproach. Though your anger springs from no private malice, and the people do not deeply resent you, this very quality explains why the throne recognizes you and the times esteem you. I speak not to flatter but to sound a note of caution.

    "Know that taming domestic beasts differs wholly from subduing wild creatures. A horse accepts the bridle; an ox submits to the plow. Whether bearing heavy loads or laboring hard, they obey without resistance—all because they have learned the way. Yet place a crown upon a monkey and it will tear it asunder and flee; strike a tiger with the whip and it will claw and bite. The peoples of your former provinces had grown accustomed to propriety and righteousness, resembling tamed beasts—thus command and authority alone sufficed to keep them obedient. But the people now awaiting you are fierce and untamed, ignorant of ritual and law, wild as beasts in their nature. If you impose severity alone, they will bite or flee.

    "I counsel you to temper your strength with breadth, to govern through generosity, and to hold firm in sincerity. Let the people come to love you and attach themselves willingly—thus you transform wild creatures into those dwelling peacefully within the enclosure. Then may you nurture and guide them with accumulated authority until they move not. Is this not the easier path?

    "As for those who remain in the mountains, set your traps and dig your pitfalls to await their coming, ensuring only that they harm not your fields—do not pursue them deep into the wilderness. Heed this warning. Within, cultivate compassion and gentleness; without, extinguish all seeds of conflict. Should you one day return to serve in the capital deliberating upon defense and restoration, you will find that nothing exceeds what you have learned here. Apply yourself with diligence to this task."
  footnotes:
    - Gongju (孔州) refers to the ancient name of the region later known as Kyongwon, in what is now North Korea's Kangwon Province
    - The 'Late Majesty' (太上王) refers to the founder's father who had abdicated; the reference to elevated ancestors reflects the practice of posthumous royal honors
    - Shin Gong's previous service as a high minister holding rank ('相臣') demonstrates his importance and makes his assignment to the frontier post all the more significant
    - The extended metaphor of wild beasts versus domesticated animals reflects classical Chinese political philosophy regarding the governance of civilized versus uncivilized peoples
